<subSubSection lastPageId="74" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="73.[151,1437,1867,2036]" lastBlockId="74.[151,1437,151,356]" lastPageId="74" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1867,1891]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Remarks:</emphasis>
Because the species was treated as 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Ellerman &amp; Morrison-Scott" authorityYear="1951" box="[720,821,1867,1892]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="meles">
<emphasis box="[720,821,1867,1892]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">M. meles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for a long time, the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Ellerman &amp; Morrison-Scott" authorityYear="1951" box="[1119,1221,1867,1892]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="meles">
<emphasis box="[1119,1221,1867,1892]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">M. meles</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
became frequently used in 
<collectingCountry box="[244,316,1904,1927]" name="South Korea" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Korea</collectingCountry>
. Based on DNA analysis (
<bibRefCitation author="Tashima" box="[624,857,1903,1928]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Tashima" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" pagination="293 - 303" refId="ref122115" refString="Tashima, S., Kaneko, Y., Anezaki, T., Baba, M., Yachimori, S., Abramov, A. V., Saveljev, A. P. &amp; Masuda, R. (2011) Phylogeographic sympatry and isolation of the Eurasian badgers (Meles, Mustelidae, Carnivora): implications for an alternative analysis using maternally as well as paternally inherited genes. Zoological Science, 28, 293 - 303. https: // doi. org / 10.2108 / zsj. 28.293" type="journal article" year="2011">
Tashima 
<emphasis box="[730,789,1903,1928]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
), the species complex of the Eurasian badger was divided into four lineages, Japanese (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Temminck" authorityYear="1844" box="[593,738,1939,1964]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anakuma">
<emphasis box="[593,738,1939,1964]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">M. anakuma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); western Eurasian (
<emphasis box="[986,1168,1939,1964]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Ellerman &amp; Morrison-Scott" authorityYear="1951" box="[986,1092,1939,1964]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="meles">M. meles</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Ellerman &amp; Morrison-Scott" authorityYear="1951" box="[1104,1168,1939,1964]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="meles">meles</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
European subspecies); Caucasian (
<taxonomicName authority="Transcaucasian" authorityName="Transcaucasian" box="[286,698,1975,2000]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Chordata" rank="subSpecies" species="meles" subSpecies="canascens">
<emphasis box="[286,516,1975,2000]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">M. meles canascens</emphasis>
Transcaucasian
</taxonomicName>
subspecies); and eastern Eurasian (
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hodgson" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[1115,1252,1975,2000]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucurus">
<emphasis box="[1115,1252,1975,2000]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">M. leucurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Abramov and Puzachenko" firstAuthor="Abramov" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" pagination="641 - 655" refId="ref94022" refString="Abramov, A. V. &amp; Puzachenko, A. Y. (2006) Geographical variability of skull and taxonomy of Eurasian badgers (Mustelidae, Meles). Zoologicheskii Zhurnal, 85, 641 - 655. [in Russian]" type="journal article" year="2006">Abramov and Puzachenko (2006)</bibRefCitation>
delineated two subspecies, 
<emphasis box="[676,831,2011,2036]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
M. l. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hodgson" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[734,831,2011,2036]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucurus">leucurus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[883,1062,2011,2036]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
M. l. 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Han" authorityYear="1994" box="[941,1058,2012,2035]" class="Mammalia" family="Erinaceidae" genus="Erinaceus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Erinaceomorpha" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amurensis">amurensis</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
based on morphometric analysis; the Korean badger was regarded as 
<emphasis box="[554,729,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
M. l. 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Han" authorityYear="1994" box="[615,729,153,176]" class="Mammalia" family="Erinaceidae" genus="Erinaceus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Erinaceomorpha" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amurensis">amurensis</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Koh" box="[860,1069,151,176]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Koh" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" pagination="1 - 8" refId="ref109407" refString="Koh, H. S., Kryukov, A., Oh, J. G., Bayarkhagva, D., Yang, B. G., Ahn, N. H. &amp; Bazarsad, D. (2014 b) Two sympatric phylogroups of the Asian badger Meles leucurus (Carnivora: Mammalia) identified by mitochondrial DNA cytochrome b gene sequences. Russian Journal of Theriology, 13, 1 - 8. https: // doi. org / 10.15298 / rusjtheriol. 13.1.01" type="journal article" year="2014" yearSuffix="b">
Koh 
<emphasis box="[916,964,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">et al</emphasis>
. (2014b)
</bibRefCitation>
rejected the species status of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Temminck" authorityYear="1844" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anakuma">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">M. anakuma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and considered 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hodgson" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[436,570,188,213]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucurus">
<emphasis box="[436,570,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">M. leucurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a monotypic species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="74.[151,1437,151,356]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,447,223,248]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Conservation status:</emphasis>
Since traditional medicine began using gall bladders of this badger as a substitute for bear gall bladders, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hodgson" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[366,500,260,285]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucurus">
<emphasis box="[366,500,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">M. leucurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
populations have decreased. 
<collectingRegion box="[833,899,260,285]" country="South Korea" name="Seoul" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Seoul</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[911,979,260,285]" country="South Korea" name="Ulsan" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Ulsan</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[1040,1261,260,285]" country="South Korea" name="Jeonnam" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Jeollanam Province</collectingRegion>
designated this species as provincially protected since 2002. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hodgson" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[674,847,295,320]" class="Mammalia" family="Mustelidae" genus="Meles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="leucurus">
<emphasis box="[674,847,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Meles leucurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[889,1032,295,320]" name="South Korea" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">South Korea</collectingCountry>
is listed ‘Near Threatened’ (NIBR 2012).
</paragraph>
